Disaster declerations were made in the communities of Juneau, Haines, Sitka, Hoonah, and Pelican totaling over 4 million dollars. Early November high elevation snowpack ran-off during the warm up and helped contribute to the problems. As is typical during these extended periods of heavy rainfall in Southeast Alaska, the steep mountain slopes that run off into the channels experienced numerous landslides. Several homes were damaged by these landslides in the Juneau and Haines areas. Streams and creeks swelled to bankfull levels, though no river flooding was reported. Backed up culverts caused erosion beneath roadways. Major damage occurred on the Haines road system due to this type of erosion. Flooded basements were also reported in many areas. Winds associated with the frontal passages complicated matters and caused widespread treefall throughout the Tongass National Forest. Numerous power outages were reported as well. Widespread flooding in Juneau

column17: 8.0772’’ of rain in 24 hours, 10.033’’ in 72, Hoonah residents are cleaning up after a mudslide blocked a road, knocked a house off its foundation and caused a power outage. Mayor Albert Dick says heavy rains on Monday night left the whole town flooded. He says road crews were working day and night to keep culverts open. Dick says the mudslide was about 200 yards long and 50 feet wide. It pushed Paul and Mary Rudolph's house about two feet off its foundation and sent trees through the main floor. The couple wasn't at home at the time. Dick says the mudslide occurred after a 24-hour downpour hit ground already soaked by weeks of rain. He says he's concerned the towns main paved road will be undermined. And he estimates there's been about $40,000 worth of damage to the town."this is the first time we have ever had something like this in Hoonah.
